514
00:26:18.096 --> 00:26:19.136 A:middle
&gt;&gt; So, good morning.

515
00:26:19.136 --> 00:26:20.056 A:middle
My name is Karl Hsu.

516
00:26:20.056 --> 00:26:21.906 A:middle
I also work on the
iOS Photos Frameworks.

517
00:26:23.006 --> 00:26:25.816 A:middle
So we've just spent a
little while talking

518
00:26:25.816 --> 00:26:28.816 A:middle
about how you can discover
and work with the structure

519
00:26:28.896 --> 00:26:30.196 A:middle
of the user's photo library.

520
00:26:30.196 --> 00:26:30.926 A:middle
And that's great.

521
00:26:31.236 --> 00:26:33.266 A:middle
But we're missing
a key ingredient

522
00:26:33.566 --> 00:26:35.406 A:middle
because it is the
user's photo library.

523
00:26:35.946 --> 00:26:37.446 A:middle
How do we actually get a hold of

524
00:26:37.446 --> 00:26:39.906 A:middle
and display image
and video data?

525
00:26:41.456 --> 00:26:44.406 A:middle
Before we begin,
it's useful to know

526
00:26:44.746 --> 00:26:49.736 A:middle
that the user's photo library
actually caches a variety

527
00:26:49.736 --> 00:26:51.636 A:middle
of representations
for each asset.

528
00:26:51.866 --> 00:26:54.916 A:middle
For images, we might
have representations

529
00:26:54.916 --> 00:26:58.476 A:middle
that vary all the way from the
full size original all the way

530
00:26:58.476 --> 00:26:59.816 A:middle
down to small thumbnails.

531
00:27:00.526 --> 00:27:04.456 A:middle
Videos might be cached in a
variety of bitrates and sizes.

532
00:27:04.716 --> 00:27:06.836 A:middle
They might even be
streaming, okay?

533
00:27:07.486 --> 00:27:11.256 A:middle
With iCloud Photo Library we
might not actually have all

534
00:27:11.286 --> 00:27:13.896 A:middle
of those representations
cached on disks.

535
00:27:13.896 --> 00:27:15.906 A:middle
Some or all of them,
or in some cases,

536
00:27:15.906 --> 00:27:17.376 A:middle
even none of them
might be available.

537
00:27:18.246 --> 00:27:20.206 A:middle
That makes it kind of
a pain when you want

538
00:27:20.206 --> 00:27:21.206 A:middle
to display image data.

539
00:27:21.876 --> 00:27:24.346 A:middle
So what we have is
we provide you

540
00:27:24.906 --> 00:27:26.806 A:middle
with a class, the
PHImageManager.

541
00:27:27.306 --> 00:27:31.956 A:middle
The PHImageManager's job is to
abstract a way, sort of this,

542
00:27:31.956 --> 00:27:34.016 A:middle
your decision, from
having to decide, you know,

543
00:27:34.016 --> 00:27:36.886 A:middle
do I want a thumbnail, do I
want a medium size, a large?

544
00:27:36.986 --> 00:27:37.576 A:middle
What do you want?

545
00:27:37.856 --> 00:27:40.246 A:middle
So basically it's
a usage-based API.

546
00:27:40.756 --> 00:27:43.606 A:middle
For images, you tell us how
big do you want the image?

547
00:27:43.606 --> 00:27:44.886 A:middle
What are you trying
to do with it?

548
00:27:44.886 --> 00:27:47.016 A:middle
Are you trying to display it
in a small grid on the screen?

549
00:27:47.016 --> 00:27:48.916 A:middle
Are you trying to --
you want the full size?

550
00:27:48.916 --> 00:27:50.236 A:middle
You want something
that's screen size?

551
00:27:50.236 --> 00:27:51.866 A:middle
And we'll try to find the right,

552
00:27:51.866 --> 00:27:54.146 A:middle
the best available
representation we have for you.

553
00:27:54.666 --> 00:27:55.776 A:middle
Similarly, videos.

554
00:27:56.006 --> 00:27:57.426 A:middle
You tell us what
quality you'd like

555
00:27:57.426 --> 00:27:58.736 A:middle
and what you plan
on doing with it.

556
00:27:58.736 --> 00:28:00.106 A:middle
Is it just for user playback?

557
00:28:00.106 --> 00:28:01.466 A:middle
Are you planning
on exporting it?

558
00:28:01.466 --> 00:28:03.076 A:middle
Or are you going to work
with it in some other way?

559
00:28:03.666 --> 00:28:05.946 A:middle
And we'll try to pick
the right representation.

560
00:28:07.506 --> 00:28:08.866 A:middle
One key thing here is

561
00:28:08.866 --> 00:28:12.416 A:middle
that unlike the Model
[inaudible] API,

562
00:28:12.916 --> 00:28:14.486 A:middle
which is largely synchronous,

563
00:28:15.336 --> 00:28:19.486 A:middle
the image request APIs
are largely asynchronous.

564
00:28:20.176 --> 00:28:23.356 A:middle
And that's because even if
the data is available locally,

565
00:28:23.356 --> 00:28:26.596 A:middle
we may have to do work before
we can hand you the data.

566
00:28:26.596 --> 00:28:28.146 A:middle
JPEGs have to be
read off a disk.

567
00:28:28.146 --> 00:28:29.136 A:middle
They have to be decoded.

568
00:28:29.726 --> 00:28:33.716 A:middle
But the most important case
is in the case of something

569
00:28:33.716 --> 00:28:34.996 A:middle
like iCloud Photo Library,

570
00:28:35.256 --> 00:28:38.636 A:middle
we may not have the data
locally available at all, right?

571
00:28:38.636 --> 00:28:41.136 A:middle
We may have to go out
to the network, get it,

572
00:28:41.416 --> 00:28:44.036 A:middle
and then bring it back to you.

573
00:28:44.266 --> 00:28:46.676 A:middle
So let's take a quick look
at what that looks like.

574
00:28:46.926 --> 00:28:49.856 A:middle
This is a very straightforward
fetch request.

575
00:28:49.996 --> 00:28:51.516 A:middle
I'm sorry, image request.

576
00:28:52.636 --> 00:28:55.336 A:middle
In this case we're
trying to fill sort

577
00:28:55.336 --> 00:28:58.166 A:middle
of a straightforward
four-across grid on an iPhone.

578
00:28:58.536 --> 00:29:01.106 A:middle
It turns out to be
about 160 by 160 pixels.

579
00:29:01.696 --> 00:29:03.556 A:middle
So we set the target size,

580
00:29:03.556 --> 00:29:06.336 A:middle
we tell it that the image
should fill that target size,

581
00:29:06.336 --> 00:29:07.876 A:middle
and then we issue the request.

582
00:29:07.876 --> 00:29:08.716 A:middle
And when it comes back,

583
00:29:09.266 --> 00:29:11.706 A:middle
if there's any image data
available, we'll hand it to you.

584
00:29:11.706 --> 00:29:14.916 A:middle
The Info Dictionary is there and
we'll tell you a little bit more

585
00:29:14.916 --> 00:29:16.146 A:middle
about what we handed you back.

586
00:29:16.146 --> 00:29:17.826 A:middle
Specifically, is
it a substandard,

587
00:29:17.826 --> 00:29:19.096 A:middle
it is the right size?

588
00:29:19.656 --> 00:29:19.966 A:middle
It's good.

589
00:29:21.316 --> 00:29:23.016 A:middle
So let's take a look
at a little bit more

590
00:29:23.016 --> 00:29:24.356 A:middle
of an advanced image request.

591
00:29:25.486 --> 00:29:29.086 A:middle
So when you want to make
a more advanced request,

592
00:29:29.086 --> 00:29:30.986 A:middle
you create an
ImageRequestOption.

593
00:29:31.876 --> 00:29:34.516 A:middle
In this case, after
I create the option,

594
00:29:35.096 --> 00:29:37.356 A:middle
I really want this photo, right?

595
00:29:38.046 --> 00:29:40.136 A:middle
So I'm going to tell the
option that, yes, it's allowed

596
00:29:40.136 --> 00:29:41.236 A:middle
to go out to the network.

597
00:29:41.236 --> 00:29:43.906 A:middle
It can go out to iCloud
and fetch the data down.

598
00:29:44.156 --> 00:29:45.786 A:middle
And because that might
take a little bit of time,

599
00:29:45.786 --> 00:29:47.306 A:middle
I'd like a progress
handler as well.

600
00:29:47.786 --> 00:29:48.936 A:middle
Again, this is a good idea.

601
00:29:48.936 --> 00:29:50.526 A:middle
You can always show
the user that we're,

602
00:29:50.526 --> 00:29:52.336 A:middle
in fact, doing work, okay?

603
00:29:52.336 --> 00:29:56.036 A:middle
And then, finally, just
set it as an option

604
00:29:56.036 --> 00:29:57.486 A:middle
when you actually
make the request.

605
00:30:00.396 --> 00:30:05.146 A:middle
I want to spend a second
and talk about the callback

606
00:30:05.676 --> 00:30:07.316 A:middle
that actually produces the data.

607
00:30:07.696 --> 00:30:09.176 A:middle
There's two things
to keep in mind.

608
00:30:09.176 --> 00:30:14.016 A:middle
Again, this block will be
called back on the main thread.

609
00:30:14.546 --> 00:30:17.296 A:middle
And the reason is
because the feeling is

610
00:30:17.296 --> 00:30:18.916 A:middle
that generally you
want to use it for --

611
00:30:18.916 --> 00:30:19.996 A:middle
if it's an asynchronous
callback,

612
00:30:19.996 --> 00:30:22.046 A:middle
you're typically using it for
display on the main thread.

613
00:30:22.726 --> 00:30:24.856 A:middle
There's an optional way to
make a synchronous request

614
00:30:24.856 --> 00:30:26.286 A:middle
if you're working in
background threads.

615
00:30:26.736 --> 00:30:28.656 A:middle
Okay. The other thing
is actually,

616
00:30:29.306 --> 00:30:32.516 A:middle
this block can be called
multiple times for each request

617
00:30:32.926 --> 00:30:37.906 A:middle
because it turns out that a
really common UIDesign is the

618
00:30:37.906 --> 00:30:40.926 A:middle
user wants to see their image
data as soon as possible.

619
00:30:41.546 --> 00:30:44.726 A:middle
So if we have any image
data available we'll return

620
00:30:44.726 --> 00:30:46.586 A:middle
that to you right away.

621
00:30:47.836 --> 00:30:50.346 A:middle
And then, if that
isn't sufficient

622
00:30:50.466 --> 00:30:53.116 A:middle
to fulfill your request,
we go out,

623
00:30:53.526 --> 00:30:56.606 A:middle
possibly to the disk,
possibly to iCloud.

624
00:30:56.836 --> 00:30:58.796 A:middle
We'll go get the data
and, when it arrives,

625
00:30:58.856 --> 00:31:00.966 A:middle
then we'll call it
a second time.

626
00:31:01.356 --> 00:31:03.356 A:middle
[ Applause ]

627
00:31:03.696 --> 00:31:04.076 A:middle
Thank you.

628
00:31:04.996 --> 00:31:06.806 A:middle
Of course, if the
data's already available,

629
00:31:07.086 --> 00:31:08.886 A:middle
then you only get
the first callout.

630
00:31:09.396 --> 00:31:12.606 A:middle
Let's take a quick look
at requesting videos.

631
00:31:12.606 --> 00:31:15.616 A:middle
So in this case, the user
has scrolled to some video

632
00:31:15.616 --> 00:31:17.056 A:middle
and they just want playback.

633
00:31:17.216 --> 00:31:19.946 A:middle
So we're requesting a
PlayerItem for the video.

634
00:31:20.006 --> 00:31:22.366 A:middle
When we get back a player item
you can create an AVPlayer

635
00:31:22.366 --> 00:31:23.376 A:middle
out of it.

636
00:31:23.376 --> 00:31:24.776 A:middle
It looks very much
like the Image Request.

637
00:31:24.776 --> 00:31:25.706 A:middle
It's pretty straightforward.

638
00:31:26.656 --> 00:31:30.426 A:middle
And, again, if we want a
more advanced request --

639
00:31:30.536 --> 00:31:35.416 A:middle
let's say, the user now
wants to push this video

640
00:31:35.446 --> 00:31:37.846 A:middle
up to their own sharing service,
a different sharing service.

641
00:31:38.166 --> 00:31:40.586 A:middle
So now we're going to
create a VideoRequestOption.

642
00:31:41.046 --> 00:31:44.736 A:middle
And, of course, because
we're sharing it,

643
00:31:44.846 --> 00:31:47.806 A:middle
we want it to be high quality.

644
00:31:47.806 --> 00:31:51.896 A:middle
Maybe you're on an iPhone and
you wanted the full 1080P, okay?

645
00:31:52.516 --> 00:31:53.916 A:middle
So, we want it to
be high quality

646
00:31:53.976 --> 00:31:55.386 A:middle
and if it's not available --

647
00:31:56.036 --> 00:31:57.266 A:middle
because we were playing
it before.

648
00:31:57.266 --> 00:31:58.346 A:middle
That might have been streaming.

649
00:31:58.876 --> 00:32:00.626 A:middle
We are, you know, we say,
okay, it's all right.

650
00:32:00.626 --> 00:32:02.286 A:middle
You can go out to the
network and download it.

651
00:32:02.576 --> 00:32:04.866 A:middle
And it's particularly
important for videos, of course,

652
00:32:04.866 --> 00:32:08.106 A:middle
to have progress because
videos can be very large.

653
00:32:08.696 --> 00:32:11.026 A:middle
And then, finally,
we set the option.

654
00:32:11.326 --> 00:32:13.636 A:middle
Note here that we're actually
using a slightly different API.

655
00:32:13.636 --> 00:32:18.486 A:middle
We're specifically requesting
an export session rather

656
00:32:18.486 --> 00:32:19.966 A:middle
than a playback item.

657
00:32:20.496 --> 00:32:22.356 A:middle
So this is good.

658
00:32:23.596 --> 00:32:26.286 A:middle
We can fetch individual images,
and that works pretty well.

659
00:32:26.446 --> 00:32:30.656 A:middle
But, it's really common
for a photo app to want

660
00:32:30.656 --> 00:32:32.066 A:middle
to show lots of images.

661
00:32:32.066 --> 00:32:33.566 A:middle
The user doesn't want to scroll

662
00:32:33.566 --> 00:32:34.966 A:middle
through their images
one at a time.

663
00:32:35.326 --> 00:32:37.226 A:middle
They want to see
a grid of images

664
00:32:37.226 --> 00:32:41.946 A:middle
in either a regular square grid
or a more interesting, you know,

665
00:32:41.946 --> 00:32:43.516 A:middle
tile and brick mortar layout.

666
00:32:43.816 --> 00:32:45.626 A:middle
That poses some performance
problems.

667
00:32:45.626 --> 00:32:47.936 A:middle
Even if the individual
images are relatively cheap,

668
00:32:47.936 --> 00:32:48.676 A:middle
there's a lot of them.

669
00:32:49.216 --> 00:32:50.276 A:middle
So what do we do?

670
00:32:50.276 --> 00:32:52.836 A:middle
The general thing that people
want to do is you create a cache

671
00:32:52.836 --> 00:32:54.446 A:middle
around what the user's
looking at.

672
00:32:54.446 --> 00:32:56.256 A:middle
You figure out which
direction they're going

673
00:32:56.256 --> 00:32:58.346 A:middle
and you start caching
ahead of them

674
00:32:58.346 --> 00:32:59.666 A:middle
and you stop caching behind.

675
00:33:00.126 --> 00:33:01.506 A:middle
So this is a pain, right?

676
00:33:01.826 --> 00:33:03.856 A:middle
You kind of have to
track all of this data.

677
00:33:03.856 --> 00:33:06.276 A:middle
You have to know to retrieve
stuff from that cache.

678
00:33:06.496 --> 00:33:08.676 A:middle
We've already got an API
for doing a lot of this.

679
00:33:09.616 --> 00:33:13.246 A:middle
And that API is the
PHCachingImageManager, okay?

680
00:33:13.766 --> 00:33:17.216 A:middle
The caching image manager's job
is exactly what it sounds like.

681
00:33:17.216 --> 00:33:20.496 A:middle
Its job is to cache images
on your behalf, okay?

682
00:33:20.966 --> 00:33:23.616 A:middle
As you make requests against
the caching image manager,

683
00:33:23.686 --> 00:33:26.526 A:middle
if it's in its cache, it
will return that directly.

684
00:33:26.526 --> 00:33:28.736 A:middle
And if not, it will
automatically fall back

685
00:33:28.736 --> 00:33:30.416 A:middle
to the default image
request behavior.

686
00:33:31.066 --> 00:33:33.116 A:middle
Now the general suggestion is

687
00:33:33.116 --> 00:33:36.006 A:middle
that you create a caching
image manager for each sort

688
00:33:36.006 --> 00:33:38.776 A:middle
of distinct view controller
that you have in your app.

689
00:33:39.006 --> 00:33:41.816 A:middle
That's because each view
controller typically has its own

690
00:33:41.816 --> 00:33:45.126 A:middle
display of image data, right?

691
00:33:45.126 --> 00:33:47.856 A:middle
You know, a grid view
controller is going to behave --

692
00:33:47.856 --> 00:33:49.596 A:middle
it's going to need
different caching behaviors

693
00:33:49.596 --> 00:33:52.296 A:middle
than like a one-up view where
you're scrolling through.

694
00:33:53.616 --> 00:33:55.496 A:middle
So let's take a quick look at
what I'm talking about here.

695
00:33:55.496 --> 00:33:57.486 A:middle
So we have the user's phone.

696
00:33:58.226 --> 00:34:00.106 A:middle
They're looking at
some nice pictures

697
00:34:00.106 --> 00:34:01.386 A:middle
and they're scrolling
through it.

698
00:34:01.676 --> 00:34:03.056 A:middle
Now this is what the user sees.

699
00:34:03.996 --> 00:34:07.376 A:middle
But we know that underneath what
they actually have is this sort

700
00:34:07.376 --> 00:34:10.856 A:middle
of long scroll view of
photos above and behind.

701
00:34:10.956 --> 00:34:13.096 A:middle
And what they only see
is the visible range.

702
00:34:13.706 --> 00:34:17.366 A:middle
So as they're scrolling down,
we want to start caching ahead

703
00:34:17.366 --> 00:34:20.636 A:middle
of where they are so that the
data's available immediately

704
00:34:21.085 --> 00:34:23.496 A:middle
when you need to
display it to the user.

705
00:34:23.946 --> 00:34:25.616 A:middle
And, of course, for
memory reasons,

706
00:34:25.616 --> 00:34:27.156 A:middle
we want to stop caching behind.

707
00:34:27.505 --> 00:34:29.686 A:middle
You just sort of calculate
this range and maintain it,

708
00:34:30.266 --> 00:34:32.726 A:middle
and as you scroll
just keep updating.

709
00:34:33.896 --> 00:34:38.106 A:middle
Okay? The API for the caching
image manager is actually

710
00:34:38.106 --> 00:34:38.936 A:middle
pretty straightforward.

711
00:34:39.376 --> 00:34:42.176 A:middle
You calculate what going
to be visible soon.

712
00:34:42.406 --> 00:34:43.735 A:middle
You tell us to start caching it.

713
00:34:44.366 --> 00:34:50.176 A:middle
And as stuff is scrolled off,
you tell us to stop caching it.

714
00:34:50.766 --> 00:34:54.726 A:middle
The only key thing here is when
you start and stop caching,

715
00:34:56.036 --> 00:34:58.936 A:middle
use the same target
size, content mode,

716
00:34:58.936 --> 00:35:02.066 A:middle
and options that you will use
for the actual request image.

717
00:35:02.686 --> 00:35:05.086 A:middle
Otherwise, we don't
know how to look it up.

718
00:35:05.346 --> 00:35:08.976 A:middle
So now we know how to get hold
of image data and we know how

719
00:35:08.976 --> 00:35:10.246 A:middle
to get a hold of it fast.

720
00:35:10.806 --> 00:35:12.746 A:middle
We know how to get a
hold of video data.

721
00:35:12.746 --> 00:35:16.096 A:middle
But, of course, just looking
at data's only half the story.

722
00:35:16.906 --> 00:35:19.466 A:middle
Users love to touch
their photos.

723
00:35:19.466 --> 00:35:22.706 A:middle
They want to adjust them, crop
it so it looks just right,

724
00:35:22.706 --> 00:35:24.436 A:middle
apply a filter so
their kids look,

725
00:35:24.436 --> 00:35:26.196 A:middle
you know, extra special pretty.

726
00:35:26.706 --> 00:35:28.776 A:middle
So let's talk about editing.

727
00:35:30.306 --> 00:35:34.316 A:middle
If the asset is editable,
the edits are now in-place.

728
00:35:34.906 --> 00:35:38.086 A:middle
Okay? You no longer need to
save your edits as a new asset.

729
00:35:38.086 --> 00:35:41.166 A:middle
You can edit any
asset that's editable.

730
00:35:41.766 --> 00:35:45.516 A:middle
The edits are, just
like in the real photos

731
00:35:45.516 --> 00:35:46.566 A:middle
out there, are nondestructive.

732
00:35:46.566 --> 00:35:48.036 A:middle
The user can always revert.

733
00:35:48.106 --> 00:35:49.816 A:middle
You can also programmatically
revert.

734
00:35:50.966 --> 00:35:53.026 A:middle
Changes that you make
are visible everywhere.

735
00:35:53.306 --> 00:35:54.516 A:middle
They'll show up in your app.

736
00:35:54.636 --> 00:35:55.906 A:middle
They show up in the photos app.

737
00:35:55.906 --> 00:36:00.116 A:middle
They show up in mail
messages, other 3rd-party apps.

738
00:36:00.666 --> 00:36:04.256 A:middle
And with iCloud Photo Library
they're actually visible

739
00:36:04.256 --> 00:36:05.956 A:middle
across all of your
devices as well.

740
00:36:07.166 --> 00:36:09.556 A:middle
Okay. So how does editing work?

741
00:36:10.156 --> 00:36:14.586 A:middle
Well, at a very simple,
basic level,

742
00:36:14.666 --> 00:36:16.606 A:middle
you ask us for an input image.

743
00:36:18.066 --> 00:36:21.036 A:middle
We hand it to you.

744
00:36:21.146 --> 00:36:24.196 A:middle
And you do whatever
transformations you want

745
00:36:24.196 --> 00:36:24.706 A:middle
to do on it.

746
00:36:24.706 --> 00:36:25.496 A:middle
You can crop it.

747
00:36:25.496 --> 00:36:26.356 A:middle
You can edit it.

748
00:36:26.356 --> 00:36:30.456 A:middle
You can go and do, you know,
pixel operations on it.

749
00:36:30.456 --> 00:36:33.956 A:middle
And when you're done,
you generate a new image,

750
00:36:33.956 --> 00:36:36.746 A:middle
a new output image,
and you hand it to us,

751
00:36:36.746 --> 00:36:38.316 A:middle
and then we save it
on top of the asset.

752
00:36:39.366 --> 00:36:39.756 A:middle
That's it.

753
00:36:40.676 --> 00:36:43.976 A:middle
So let's take a look at
how that works, okay?

754
00:36:44.836 --> 00:36:47.016 A:middle
First you want to ask
us for the input image.

755
00:36:47.586 --> 00:36:52.386 A:middle
You ask the asset for its
content editing input, okay?

756
00:36:53.056 --> 00:36:54.876 A:middle
And what that comes with is,

757
00:36:54.876 --> 00:36:57.516 A:middle
the content editing input
carries a bunch of information

758
00:36:57.516 --> 00:37:00.746 A:middle
that you'll need in order
to actually do your work.

759
00:37:01.086 --> 00:37:03.076 A:middle
It gives you a URL
with a reference

760
00:37:03.076 --> 00:37:04.236 A:middle
to the full size asset.

761
00:37:04.456 --> 00:37:06.376 A:middle
It gives you some
orientation information.

762
00:37:06.946 --> 00:37:10.026 A:middle
So, in this case, I'm
creating a core-image image

763
00:37:10.476 --> 00:37:11.936 A:middle
and I'm sure I'm
going to be using some

764
00:37:11.936 --> 00:37:14.656 A:middle
of the new filter stuff that
we have available for you now.

765
00:37:15.266 --> 00:37:17.566 A:middle
And I'm going to do some work.

766
00:37:17.876 --> 00:37:19.896 A:middle
So, I've done some work.

767
00:37:19.896 --> 00:37:20.696 A:middle
You just cropped it.

768
00:37:20.866 --> 00:37:22.006 A:middle
Maybe you applied a filter.

769
00:37:22.006 --> 00:37:22.546 A:middle
It looks great.

770
00:37:23.656 --> 00:37:24.326 A:middle
How do we save it?

771
00:37:26.006 --> 00:37:29.126 A:middle
Well, you create, ta-da,
a Content Editing Output.

772
00:37:30.166 --> 00:37:33.876 A:middle
You take your data, the
fully-rendered output,

773
00:37:33.876 --> 00:37:36.056 A:middle
save it as a JPEG,
write it to the URL,

774
00:37:36.056 --> 00:37:38.296 A:middle
and then you set
the adjustmentData.

775
00:37:39.006 --> 00:37:40.876 A:middle
I'll talk about the
adjustmentData in just a second.

776
00:37:41.176 --> 00:37:42.676 A:middle
And then how do you save it?

777
00:37:42.676 --> 00:37:45.196 A:middle
It's the same as saving
any other model change.

778
00:37:45.556 --> 00:37:49.016 A:middle
You create a asset
change request.

779
00:37:49.556 --> 00:37:51.506 A:middle
You sent the content
editing output on it,

780
00:37:52.416 --> 00:37:54.706 A:middle
put the whole thing in a
change block, and that's it.

781
00:37:55.406 --> 00:37:57.806 A:middle
So, it's a little
bit misleading,

782
00:37:57.806 --> 00:37:59.516 A:middle
actually when I said
it was that simple.

783
00:37:59.726 --> 00:38:02.476 A:middle
So there's another
wrinkle which is,

784
00:38:03.036 --> 00:38:07.926 A:middle
what if someone has
already edited that image?

785
00:38:08.926 --> 00:38:12.176 A:middle
Well, the key point
here is that actually

786
00:38:12.766 --> 00:38:17.426 A:middle
when you edit an image you
actually have the base image

787
00:38:18.136 --> 00:38:19.296 A:middle
and some adjustment data.

788
00:38:19.626 --> 00:38:21.916 A:middle
Your output image, the thing
that you give us at the end,

789
00:38:21.916 --> 00:38:22.866 A:middle
is actually the result

790
00:38:22.866 --> 00:38:25.656 A:middle
of applying this
adjustment to the base image.

791
00:38:26.266 --> 00:38:31.846 A:middle
So, really, what we hand you
is the base image plus whatever

792
00:38:31.846 --> 00:38:33.926 A:middle
adjustment data is
already on that image.

793
00:38:34.896 --> 00:38:37.266 A:middle
And that way the user
can continue editing

794
00:38:37.406 --> 00:38:41.286 A:middle
as if they had never left
their editing session, right?

795
00:38:41.486 --> 00:38:45.726 A:middle
You do a crop-down and then what
we hand you is the original plus

796
00:38:45.726 --> 00:38:48.286 A:middle
the crop information so that
you can show the user the crop,

797
00:38:48.286 --> 00:38:50.366 A:middle
that they can extend
the crop in and out.

798
00:38:50.366 --> 00:38:51.546 A:middle
They can remove it entirely.

799
00:38:51.546 --> 00:38:52.266 A:middle
They can change it.

800
00:38:52.926 --> 00:38:58.436 A:middle
And when you're done, you
hand us your output image

801
00:38:59.536 --> 00:39:01.216 A:middle
and the new adjustment data.

802
00:39:01.536 --> 00:39:03.006 A:middle
So that cycle will
just continue.

803
00:39:03.006 --> 00:39:06.286 A:middle
So the next person that asks
will get back the base image

804
00:39:06.286 --> 00:39:08.426 A:middle
plus the new adjustment data.

805
00:39:09.736 --> 00:39:11.886 A:middle
So how do you save
the adjustment data?

806
00:39:11.886 --> 00:39:13.876 A:middle
Well, the adjustment
data actually can be --

807
00:39:13.876 --> 00:39:16.336 A:middle
you use a PHAdjustmentData
object,

808
00:39:16.336 --> 00:39:20.116 A:middle
but really the data can be
whatever you want, all right?

809
00:39:20.486 --> 00:39:22.926 A:middle
For instance, it could be
the name and parameters

810
00:39:22.926 --> 00:39:24.236 A:middle
for a core image filter.

811
00:39:24.456 --> 00:39:28.586 A:middle
It could be anything that you
want that describes your edits.

812
00:39:30.226 --> 00:39:33.596 A:middle
Notice here that actually beyond
just that data we also ask you

813
00:39:33.596 --> 00:39:36.296 A:middle
to include a format
identifier and a format version.

814
00:39:37.616 --> 00:39:40.146 A:middle
They basically are a way for you

815
00:39:40.146 --> 00:39:43.766 A:middle
to identify what
edit it actually is.

816
00:39:43.766 --> 00:39:44.906 A:middle
Who did this edit?

817
00:39:44.906 --> 00:39:46.156 A:middle
What's the format of it?

818
00:39:46.666 --> 00:39:50.266 A:middle
Okay? And I'll talk a little
bit more about that in a second.

819
00:39:50.756 --> 00:39:54.286 A:middle
So, I misled you again.

820
00:39:54.746 --> 00:39:56.636 A:middle
There is one additional
case, of course.

821
00:39:57.156 --> 00:39:59.976 A:middle
What if someone else
had edited the image?

822
00:40:00.076 --> 00:40:04.786 A:middle
The scenario that I
described before is great

823
00:40:04.786 --> 00:40:07.046 A:middle
if you were the one who
previously edited it.

824
00:40:07.046 --> 00:40:11.106 A:middle
But if somebody went to App
A and they applied a crop?

825
00:40:11.106 --> 00:40:15.926 A:middle
And then they go to App B and
they want to do more editing.

826
00:40:16.236 --> 00:40:19.216 A:middle
Well, you have to tell us
whether you understand the

827
00:40:19.216 --> 00:40:19.866 A:middle
adjustment data.

828
00:40:19.866 --> 00:40:20.516 A:middle
We'll ask you.

829
00:40:20.516 --> 00:40:21.896 A:middle
We'll give you the
PHAdjustmentData.

830
00:40:22.776 --> 00:40:23.496 A:middle
And you tell us.

831
00:40:23.986 --> 00:40:25.376 A:middle
Do you understand what this is?

832
00:40:25.836 --> 00:40:26.596 A:middle
So, looking at this,

833
00:40:26.596 --> 00:40:28.666 A:middle
this actually seems
relatively straightforward

834
00:40:28.986 --> 00:40:30.566 A:middle
but we're not putting
any restrictions

835
00:40:30.566 --> 00:40:33.136 A:middle
on what the format identifier
and the format version can be.

836
00:40:33.666 --> 00:40:35.956 A:middle
Several developers from
different companies could,

837
00:40:35.956 --> 00:40:39.106 A:middle
for instance, get together
and define a common identifier

838
00:40:39.106 --> 00:40:42.066 A:middle
and version and, you know,
adjustment data format.

839
00:40:42.066 --> 00:40:45.226 A:middle
And that way the user could move
seamlessly between those apps.

840
00:40:45.226 --> 00:40:48.146 A:middle
Okay. But let's see
what happens,

841
00:40:48.236 --> 00:40:51.416 A:middle
depending on what you return
when we ask you this question,

842
00:40:51.416 --> 00:40:53.176 A:middle
can you understand this?

843
00:40:53.436 --> 00:40:55.026 A:middle
Do you understand it?

844
00:40:55.406 --> 00:40:56.566 A:middle
Yes. You say, yes.

845
00:40:56.746 --> 00:40:57.276 A:middle
That's great.

846
00:40:57.516 --> 00:41:00.706 A:middle
We'll hand you the base
image and the adjustment data

847
00:41:00.706 --> 00:41:03.786 A:middle
and you can behave as if
the user had just sort

848
00:41:03.786 --> 00:41:05.616 A:middle
of turned around, waited
a second, and come back

849
00:41:05.616 --> 00:41:06.706 A:middle
and started editing again.

850
00:41:07.266 --> 00:41:08.656 A:middle
That's sort of the ideal case.

851
00:41:08.946 --> 00:41:12.336 A:middle
But what if you tell
no, you don't?

852
00:41:12.636 --> 00:41:13.886 A:middle
Well, in this case,
unfortunately,

853
00:41:13.886 --> 00:41:14.816 A:middle
we don't have any choice.

854
00:41:14.816 --> 00:41:16.826 A:middle
We have to hand you the
fully rendered output

855
00:41:16.826 --> 00:41:17.706 A:middle
from the previous edit.

856
00:41:17.706 --> 00:41:21.576 A:middle
So the user can continue
editing but they can't back out.

857
00:41:21.576 --> 00:41:25.336 A:middle
Like, in this case, the previous
app applied a noir filter

858
00:41:25.576 --> 00:41:27.346 A:middle
and it's effectively
blocking my filter.

859
00:41:27.346 --> 00:41:29.036 A:middle
We've thrown away the
color information.

860
00:41:29.036 --> 00:41:29.536 A:middle
We don't have it.

861
00:41:30.206 --> 00:41:33.206 A:middle
If the user wants to go
back, they basically have

862
00:41:33.236 --> 00:41:34.486 A:middle
to revert back to original.

863
00:41:35.326 --> 00:41:38.186 A:middle
Okay. So, let's take
a quick demo.

